Scraping Web Data with BeautifulSoup¶

BeautifulSoup is a fantastic Python library that allows for the easy extraction of data from HTML and XML documents. Today we'll be doing a shallow dive into the API demonstrating some of this library's functionality.

I don't know about you, but when I'm working at home I like to have background noise to break up the monotony of coding. Sometimes I put on playlists while other times I watch movies, TV shows, or YouTube. Of course, I can't play any videos that are too interesting or else I'll become distracted. I find the best way to balance entertainment and distraction is put on something that I've already watched. This may include The Office; Ocean's Eleven, Twelve, Thirteen; the Harry Potter movies, or any content for one of my favorite video games Dark Souls. In fact, I've spent an embarrassing amount of time watching Dark Souls playthroughs...I wonder exactly how much time...

Aggregate video length times - first attempt¶

In the image above we see that the video length time highlighted is contained inside of a span whose parent is a div with a class name of "timestamp". We want to group all of these video length times together so we can sum up the total amount of hours I've spent watching this playlist one time. Let's start with using the requests library to get the data from this webpage. Then we'll use BeautifulSoup to parse the data and extract the salient information.

In [3]:
page = requests.get("https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL8EDF103C6EBECA64")
soup = BeautifulSoup(page.text, 'html.parser')

# `find_all` returns a list of bs4.element.Tag objects for every matching element
# the first positional argument is the HTML element tag to search for while the second positional argument
# is a dictionary of HTML element attributes to narrow the result list further
time_divs = soup.find_all('div', {'class': 'timestamp'})

# `find` returns a single bs4.element.Tag for the first matching element
times = [d.find('span').text for d in time_divs]

for time in times[:5]:
    print(time)
print('\n', len(times))

13:40
13:21
12:28
6:34
11:40

 100

Alright, lookin' good. We've correctly isolated the video lengths from the playlist webpage -- but wait -- something's not right. We're only collecting 100 video lengths and I know this playlist had 190 videos in it. If we scroll down to the bottom of the webpage we can see that YouTube's pagination prevents us from immediately viewing all of the videos in this playlist.

In [4]:
Image("yt_bottom_of_page.png")
Out[4]:

Circumventing pagination limits¶

There are two approaches to getting around this obstacle.

The more involved but also more robust solution would be to use Selenium. Selenium is a browser automation tool that uses a browser driver to make requests and receive responses. Selenium allows us to "click" on the span tag with class name of "load-more-text" (i.e. the "Load" button at the bottom of the playlist page) which will load another full page of up to 100 videos. This would enable the programmatic ensurance that all content is loaded before continuing on to the next step.

Since this is a simple demonstration, we'll go with the simpler approach. Let's just manually click the "Load" button on the page to fetch all of the videos in the playlist, open the developer tools, click "Elements" to see the full HTML, right-click on the opening HTML and choose "copy" > "copy element". Now we can paste the full HTML into a new file and parse this file with BeautifulSoup.

Aggregate video length times - second attempt¶

In [6]:
soup = BeautifulSoup(open('yt_page.html', 'r').read(), 'html.parser')
times = [d.find('span').text for d in soup.find_all('div', {'class': 'timestamp'})]
for time in times[:5]:
    print(time)
print('\n', len(times))

13:40
13:21
12:28
6:34
11:40

 190

Nice. We're still able to get video lengths from the copied HTML but now the full playlist is represented in the document. Let's write a helper function that we can use to convert the string representation of video lengths into integers. Then we can use this to sum up all of the video lengths in the playlist.

In [7]:
def convert_time(string):
    minutes_seconds = string.split(':')
    return int(minutes_seconds[0]) + int(minutes_seconds[1])/60

total_minutes = sum([convert_time(t) for t in times])
print(total_minutes/60)

52.891666666666644

That's it!¶

I've spent just a little less than 53 hours watching Dark Souls With James -- actually, since I just finished my second watch through, that would be a little less than 106 hours watched.

The more positive perspective is that I've spent at least a whooping 106 houurs working on assignments, personal projects, and skill enrichment!
